  <sec sec-type="data-availability" id="sec22">
    <title>Software and data availability</title>
    <p>HiC1Dmetrics (<ext-link xlink:href="https://github.com/wangjk321/HiC1Dmetrics" ext-link-type="uri">https://github.com/wangjk321/HiC1Dmetrics</ext-link>) was written with Python3 and released in <ext-link xlink:href="https://pypi.org/project/h1d/" ext-link-type="uri">https://pypi.org/project/h1d/</ext-link>. Detailed requirements and usage are introduced in <ext-link xlink:href="https://h1d.readthedocs.io/" ext-link-type="uri">https://h1d.readthedocs.io/</ext-link>. HiC1Dmetrics uses acceptable memory (~ gigabytes) on high-resolution (i.e. ≥5 kb) Hi-C, but the fine-resolution data (e.g. &lt;1 kb) may use much more memory. We also provide a Streamlit-based web application (<ext-link xlink:href="http://hic1d.herokuapp.com" ext-link-type="uri">http://hic1d.herokuapp.com</ext-link>) that is easier and more convenient for analyzing 1D metrics from Hi-C samples. The datasets used in this study are listed in <xref rid="sup2" ref-type="supplementary-material">Supplementary Table S1</xref> and available at the Gene Expression Omnibus.</p>
